DIGEST
SB 342 Original 2026 Regular Session Barrow
Present law (Title 18 of the Louisiana Revised Statutes) provides for the administration of
elections, including voter registration, early voting, absentee voting, polling place conduct,
voter roll maintenance, and penalties for election offenses.
Present law prohibits voter intimidation and certain election offenses, including coercion,
fraud, and interference with the election process.
Present law establishes deadlines and procedures for voter registration, including in-person
and online registration.
Present law provides for campaign-free zones and restrictions on electioneering at polling
places.
Present law authorizes registrars of voters and the secretary of state to conduct voter roll
maintenance and removal of ineligible voters pursuant to specified procedures.
Proposed law enacts new law to be designated as the "Voter Protection Act" and to be
codified at R.S. 18:1955 - 1962.
Proposed law provides definitions applicable to the new Subpart.
Proposed law prohibits knowingly or intentionally intimidating, deceiving, misinforming,
or coercing any voter, prospective voter, or voter assistance provider regarding voter
eligibility, registration requirements, polling locations, voting times or dates, or voting
procedures.
Proposed law provides that violations are punishable as a misdemeanor and provides
enhanced felony penalties for organized or systematic voter suppression.
Proposed law requires the secretary of state to develop standardized, accessible voter
registration materials, including multilingual materials reflective of the state's demographics.
Proposed law extends the voter registration deadline by seven days beyond the deadline
otherwise provided by law.
Proposed law requires expansion of secure online and mobile-friendly voter registration
services.
Proposed law creates a 600 foot no-interference zone around polling places during early
voting and on election day prohibiting electioneering, dissemination of false voting
information, or acts of persuasion targeting voters.
Proposed law requires polling places to display signage explaining voter rights and requires
